rmk: Two pairs of adult Mute Swans were present but not in each other's company on Lough Bofin, a large brackish lake on Inishbofin. At times the pairs drifted up to 100m apart before swimming back towards each other, although they never came within 20m. Calls came from each pair. As I watched all four, it became obvious that only the adult females (each accompanied by an adult male) were calling to each other. During the first two seconds of the recording you can hear one being answered by the other. Due to a gusty wind drowning out calls, I had to delete several broadcasts in which one female answered the other. However, the two were exchanging calls regularly. At 0:11 a male calls. His voice is different and has a snorting or sneezing quality. Unfortunately, just as the male 'snorts', the more distant of the two females calls in response to the female that accompanied the snorting male. Her response - because she was at least 50m away - is almost masked by the male's vocalisation. Nonetheless, the 'conversation' (exchange of calls) between two females can be discerned.
